<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Participants `Optimistic' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2303093494 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in English 0903 
GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2303093494 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cease-fire negotiations between the Croatian 
Government and rebel Serb authorities in the protected areas are 
to resume on the 29th of this month. The talks were adjourned 
about 1230 last night, after 13 hours. The most difficult 
points were details of how to implement the cease-fire and to 
disengage forces on the ground. 
  According to HINA, all the participants were optimistic, and 
the Russian special envoy, Vitaliy Churkin, described the 
situation as favorable for reaching an agreement. The American 
ambassador stated that the countries involved in the talks 
firmly support Croatian integrity, but the problem must be 
solved by peaceful means. The leader of the Croatian 
delegation, Hrvoje Sarinic, said that the fact that the talks 
would resume next Tuesday spoke for itself. He added that he 
was optimistic about reaching a solution next week. 

</TEXT>

