<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRY Official Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2303132794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1253 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2303132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 23 (TANJUG)--Head of the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia (F.R.Y.) office in Zagreb Veljko Knezevic 
said it was a "political interest of the F.R.Y. to normalize 
relations with Croatia." 
  He told TANJUG Wednesday prior to leaving for Zagreb that 
people wished normalization of relations with all Yugoslavia's 
neighbors, especially with Croatia because the situation there 
was most complex. Knezevic stressed that Croatia behaved 
differently on the international scene as opposed to bilateral 
contacts. 
  The Yugoslav office in Zagreb was opened on the basis of an 
agreement the foreign ministers of F.R.Y. and Croatia signed on 
January 19 this year in Geneva. The office of Croatia in 
Belgrade was to be opened soon. 
  Speaking about the first round of talks between the Republic 
of Serb Krajina (R.S.K.) and Croatia in Zagreb on Tuesday, 
Knezevic said that normalization between Knin and Zagreb would 
surely contribute also to normalization of relations between 
Belgrade and Zagreb. 
  "It is very important that the talks are to be continued," 
assessed Knezevic and emphasized that "normalization and 
political solutions of problems between the R.S.K. and Croatia 
would be one of the decisive factors for pacifying the situation 
in the entire territory of the former Yugoslavia." 
  The problem of the R.S.K. was one of the pressing issues in 
settling of the Yugoslav crisis. The R.S.K. was proclaimed in 
1991 in parts of the former Yugoslav Republic of Croatia with 
predominantly Serb population in response to Croatia's forcible 
secession from the former Yugoslav Federation and reducing the 
status of the Serb people from a constituent people to one of a 
national minority in the new state. 
  The subsequent armed clashes between the R.S.K. Serbs and 
the 
Zagreb authorities, which do not recognize the R.S.K., resulted 
in a decision to declare the R.S.K. a U.N.-Protected Area (UNPA) 
in the spring of 1992 until a political settlement was reached. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

