<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Hold Up Aid Convoy Bound for Maglaj </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203213594 Paris AFP in English 2125 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2203213594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, March 22 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serbs have held up 
a convoy of humanitarian aid for the Moslem enclave of Maglaj in 
northern Bosnia for at least 24 hours, the UN High Commissioner 
for Refugees (UNHCR) said here Tuesday. 
  The convoy, which left the Croatian capital Zagreb on Monday 
morning, was forced to turn back the same day by Serbian forces 
controlling the bridge at Gradiska, which links Croatia and 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, said UNHCR spokesman Peter Kessler. 
  The convoy arrived back in Zagreb on Monday night and left 
again on Tuesday morning. It reached Gradiska again at noon and 
was undergoing checks, Kessler said, blaming the delay on 
"bureaucratic difficulties." 
  Bosnian Serbs on Saturday lifted a nine-month siege of 
Maglaj. 
  The town's population of around 25,000, plus up to 75,000 
others in the surrounding enclave, had been forced to rely on 
air drops for food since October. 
  He said he hoped the convoy would get to Banja Luka, the 
main 
town under Serbian control in northern Bosnia, in time to spend 
the night there before continuing its journey to Maglaj. 
  The convoy is made up of 30 trucks, 10 of them bound for 
Maglaj, and the rest for Banja Luka, Doboj, to the north, and 
Zenica in central Bosnia. 
  On Sunday, nine UNHCR trucks loaded with 80 tonnes of food 
and medicine managed to get into Maglaj without hindrance from 
Zenica, 70 kilometres (45 miles) to the south. 
  Bosnian Serbs gave the go-ahead the same day for the second 
now delayed convoy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

