<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Road Opens to Traffic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2303114494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1113 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2303114494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 23 Mar (TANJUG)--At the prearranged hour 
this morning, the corridor linking the Serb suburbs of Lukavica 
and Ilidza via Sarajevo airport was opened to traffic. 
  Under a recent agreement between the Serb and Muslim side, a 
corridor linking the Muslim-controlled suburbs of Butmir and 
Dobrinja will also open today. 
  First, buses with civilians on board set off from Ilidza for 
Lukavica and Pale this morning. A bus left for Belgrade. 
  For the first time since the airport was handed over to 
UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] control, people from Serb 
Sarajevo were able to use the Lukavica-Ilidza road. There have 
been no traffic problems so far. 
  The Serb fighters bridge (formerly Brotherhood and Unity 
bridge), which links Grbavica with the Muslim part of Sarajevo, 
has not yet been opened to civilians because the Muslim side is 
demanding that Serb authorities in the Novo Sarajevo 
municipality remove the Srpska republic's state symbols from the 
Serb side of the border crossing. 
  The bridge and the Sarajevo-Visoko corridor via Vogosca are, 
however, expected to open to traffic later today. 

</TEXT>

