<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aid Leaves for Tuzla Unhindered </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103155494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1518 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Zvornik, March 21 (TANJUG)--A convoy of the U.N. 
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), carrying 112 tonnes of 
flour, on Monday unhindered and safely crossed Bosnian Serb 
territory on its way for Moslem-held Tuzla, eastern 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, TANJUG learned from Bosnian Serb military 
sources. 
  Owing to the efforts of the Bosnian Serbs, the relief aid 
ground routes towards Tuzla and other Moslem-, i.e. Croat-held 
towns in Bosnia, have so far remained safe and open. 
  Bosnian Serb military sources once again rejected claims by 
the international community that the opening of the Tuzla 
airport is "necessary" out of humanitarian reasons, and 
expressed doubt that other reasons and intentions lie behind the 
action. 
  The Bosnian Serbs, fearing that the Moslems could use the 
airport to illegally acquire arms under the guise of 
humanitarian aid, have made its opening conditional that the 
airport is monitored by Russian peacekeepers and that Serb 
observers control the cargo checks. 

</TEXT>

