<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus: Government Not Involved </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2203141094 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1100 
GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2203141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A little while ago, Czech radio asked Czech Prime 
Minister Vaclav Klaus to comment on today's rally staged by the 
Czech-Moravian Chamber of Trade Unions Association. 
  [Begin Klaus recording] I am not at all willing to comment 
on 
this rally because the government has not contributed one iota 
to this rally. This is simply a 100-percent, or 101-percent, 
matter of the trade unions. This has nothing to do whatsoever 
with the government. 
  The talks between the government and the trade unions have 
been conducted in an absolutely correct way, I think. A number 
of comments trade unions had regarding the amendment of the 
Labor Code have been accepted. Thus, any consideration that the 
government failed to consult these matters with the trade unions 
is an absolute lie and a fallacy. It does not necessarily 
follow that the government should accept all of the trade 
unions' comments in their entirety, as some trade union leaders 
might wish. In my view, there is nothing in this matter that 
the government would have to feel responsible for. I am getting 
reports from all over the Republic speaking about false pressure 
campaigns when trade unionists invite people to take a free trip 
to Prague, where, as part of this trip, they would briefly 
attend some kind of rally. Telephone calls, faxes, and letters 
coming from people all over the Republic clearly reveal these 
actions on the part of the trade unions. Personally, I would be 
ashamed to be a trade union leader. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

