<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daskalov Returns From Slovenia, Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203192294 Sofia BTA in English 1819 GMT 22 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203192294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, March 22 (BTA) -- Bulgaria and Slovenia 
share a desire to expand contacts and hold similar positions on 
a number of international issues, Foreign Minister Stanislav 
Daskalov said today on his return from a three-day visit to 
Slovenia. It has been the first visit at this level since 
Slovenia became independent. 
  The sides reviewed bilateral relations and expressed a 
desire 
to build a legal basis for contacts, Daskalov said. In 
Ljubljana he met with his counterpart Lojze Peterle and was 
received by President Milan Kucan, Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek 
and Parliament Chairman Herman Rigelnik. The foreign ministers 
signed an agreement on cooperation in culture, education and 
science. 
  Daskalov said that a trade agreement and probably an 
investment promotion agreement would be signed in Sofia in 
April. Agreements on double taxation relief and transport 
cooperation are also expected to be signed in the near future. 
  The two countries hold similar views on the crisis in the 
former Yugoslavia and the efforts of Bulgaria and Slovenia to 
become integrated into Europe, according to Daskalov. He said 
the two countries would open talks on establishing a free trade 
zone, perhaps during the visit here by Slovenia's Minister for 
Foreign Economic Relations Davorin Kracun on April 20, according 
to the Bulgarian foreign minister. 

</TEXT>

