<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   40,000 Attend Labor Union Demonstration </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203155694 Prague CTK in English 1505 GMT 22 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203155694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 22 (CTK) -- Journalists estimate that 
around 40,000 people attended today's demonstration called by 
the Bohemian and Moravian Chamber of Trade Unions (CMKOS) today 
at 12:00 PM in Prague's Old Town Square to warn the government 
and parliament that "the situation of employees and pensioners 
is becoming unbearable." 
  The demonstration was addressed by CMKOS Chairman Vladimir 
Petrus, who said that the unions could not be accused of 
extremism. The unionists merely considered it their 
responsibility to point out that "dissatisfaction of the people" 
threatened. They were not therefore going against parliament, 
but they asked that the government and parliament "showed social 
perceptiveness." 
  At the end of the demonstration the participants approved 
appeals to the government and to parliamentary deputies, which 
states that the union members "consider it very dangerous when 
even government bills contain attempts to transfer the burden of 
essential economic reforms on to those least able to protect 
themselves." 
  It asks ministers that the amendment to the labor code and 
the basis of the law on pension insurance be not put before 
parliament until they are properly prepared and take into 
account the union members' comments. 
  In the appeal addressed to deputies, the union members point 
to their demands concerning the making of repeated contracts, 
the position of pregnant women and mothers with small children, 
the increase in the pension age, the management of money set 
aside for pension insurance and the ban on trade union activity 
in the civil service. 
  The demonstrators were also greeted by General Secretary of 
the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions, Enzo 
Friso, who assured them of the confederation's support. 
  Messages from foreign organizations. [sentence as received] 
Concrete support was expressed by the Polish trade union 
movement Solidarity, which managed to drive radio cars with 
loudspeakers to Prague overnight, after the demonstration's 
organizers had not been able to get hold of any in the Czech 
Republic. 
  Czech Minister of Employment and Social Affairs Jindrich 
Vodicka also came to the Old Town Square, but he was for the 
most part greeted with whistles and various displays of 
indignation. Union members came to Prague from all over the 
Czech Republic in 400 buses, and filled most of the square. 

</TEXT>

