<H3> <TI>   Klaus Comments on Rally </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203155894 Prague CTK in English 1517 GMT 22 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203155894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 22 (CTK) -- Basic questions are not, 
in the contemporary Czech Republic, decided at demonstrations 
but in parliament, Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus said today, 
commenting on the midday trade union demonstration in Prague's 
Old Town Square. 
  He said the demonstration was organized by a "partial" group 
of inhabitants. While this sort of thing may have been all right 
in February 1948, it was no good for March 22, 1994, he told 
journalists. 
  Today's demonstration was organized by the Bohemian and 
Moravian Chamber of Trade Unions (CMKOS) in support of the 
withdrawal of the amendment to the employment code from 
parliament's March agenda, which begins today. The union 
members' biggest objections concerned the articles on the 
possibility of concluding repeated fixed-period contracts and on 
night work by pregnant women. 
  Unionists have negotiated these demands with the government 
and have attended the meetings of individual parliamentary 
committees, where they said they met with a lack of 
understanding of people's situations and therefore decided to 
call today's demonstration. 

</TEXT>

