<H3> <TI>   Klaus on Previous Consultations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203205194 Prague CTK in English 1914 GMT 22 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203205194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 22 (CTK) -- Czech Premier Vaclav 
Klaus said on Czech Radio today that he was not willing to 
comment on today's trade union demonstration, saying that the 
government "did not have the smallest scrap of a share in the 
demonstration," and that it "bore no relation to the government 
at all." The demonstration was organized in Prague's Old Town 
square by the Bohemian and Moravian Chamber of Trade Unions 
(CMKOS). Journalists estimated it was attended by 40,000 people. 
  He said he believed negotiations between the government and 
the unions were held in a manner that was completely correct. 
The government had accepted many of the points made by the 
unions concerning the amendment to the employment code, and so 
to say it had not consulted the unions on the matter was "utter 
lies and falsehood." 
  However, he said, the government did not have to accept all 
the unions' comments, "as some of the union leaders seem to 
wish." 
  Klaus said he had been receiving reports from all over the 
country concerning pressure placed on union members, who were 
offered a free ride to Prague in order to take part in some kind 
of demonstration for a bit. This action by unions was being 
revealed by "telephones, faxes and letters by people from all 
over the Republic," he said. 

</TEXT>

