<H3> <TI>   Survey Reveals Attitudes on Restitution Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203133494 Prague CTK in English 1033 GMT 22 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 22 (CTK) -- The majority of Czech 
citizens (65 percent) firmly believe that no further property 
should be returned to the former aristocracy and 42 percent 
oppose the restitution of church property, according to a poll 
conducted in March by the Institute for Public Opinion Research 
(IVVM) among 835 people over age 15. 
  Only two percent of those polled were definitely for the 
return of property to aristocrats and eight percent were 
definitely for the return of church property. 
  A total of 58 percent of the respondents said they were 
against the return of property to people who emigrated from 
Czechoslovakia and did not come back while only three percent 
said they favored the return of their property. 
  The restitution of church property and the return of 
property 
to emigrants was supported mostly by inhabitants of North 
Moravia. 
  Views of potential voters for various political parties 
differed considerably. Among those who favor the restitution of 
church property, 28 percent would vote for the Civic Democratic 
Party (ODS), 11 percent the Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA), 11 
percent for the Czech Social Democratic Party (CSSD), and four 
percent the Left Bloc (LB). 
  Among those who support the return of property to 
aristocrats 
19 percent would vote ODS, 8 percent ODA, 6 percent CSSD, and no 
one LB. 
  The return of property to Jewish communities is supported by 
54 percent of ODS voters, 50 percent CSSD, and 20 percent LB. 

</TEXT>

