<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jeszenszky Cited on Slovak Ties, Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2103084494 Budapest MTI in English 1738 GMT 20 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2103084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Turin, 20 March (MTI) -- "Hungary looks with hope 
to the new Slovak Government. A new government, whatever its 
composition, offers a new opportunity for a dialogue, which we 
have always encouraged," Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky said 
in Turin on Sunday [20 March]. 
  Jeszenszky, who attended a series of events marking the 
death 
centenary of 1848-49 Hungarian freedom fight leader Lajos 
Kossuth (1802-1894, died in Turin), spoke to MTI about 
Hungarian-Slovak links after the Bratislava government crisis, 
and the future of Sarajevo, the capital of Bosnia. 
  "When Hungary congratulated the newly-independent Slovakia, 
it stressed that the good wishes are also for the ethnic 
Hungarians living there. We feel reconciliation between 
Slovakia and Hungary is possible, but only if preceded by a 
compromise between Hungarians and Slovaks in Slovakia," 
Jeszenszky said. 
  He recalled his repeated negotiations with the new Prime 
Minister Jozef Moravcik, who was then foreign minister, on the 
minority problem. "I hope that the new Slovak Government will 
strive to create friendship between the two countries and their 
peoples in keeping with its original program, instead of 
fabricating artificial enemy pictures and enemies," the foreign 
minister added. 
  Regarding Saturday's rock concerts held in several large 
towns of the world at the call of Sarajevo Radio to protest 
against the raising of a new "wall" in the Bosnian capital, 
Jeszenszky -- who visited Sarajevo early this week -- pointed 
out: 
  "Everything possible should be done to prevent repetition of 
the Berlin Wall, and to promote unification of still divided 
towns in Europe and elsewhere. Administrative borders must be 
freely crossable: They can separate certain communities, but 
they must not separate the people. 

</TEXT>

