<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgian Prime Minister Makes Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Dehaene Holds Talks With Officials </H4>
<F P=102> BR2303095994 Brussels BELGA in French 2013 GMT 21 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2303095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed GGD/RHR: "Jean-Luc Dehaene Invites </F>
Hungarian Prime Minister To Belgium"; as released by Brussels 
BELGA Database] 
  [Text] Budapest, 21 Mar (BELGA) -- On Monday Belgian Prime 
Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene invited Hungarian Prime Minister Peter 
Boross to visit Belgium. 
  On the second day of his official visit to Hungary, Dehaene 
had talks on Monday with leading Magyar political, economic, 
financial, and social figures. The Belgian prime minister also 
met with President Arpad Goncz and Assembly President Gyorgy 
Szabad. 
  At a joint news conference, Dehaene and Boross both stressed 
that Belgium and Hungary -- which is seeking closer ties with 
the West -- largely share the same approach to Europe's future. 
"We support Hungary's role as the driving force" in the process 
of integrating Central European countries into European 
structures, a process which must be progressive, stated the 
Belgian prime minister, who arrived in Hungary on Sunday for a 
three-day official visit. 
  Boross stressed that Hungary -- one of the first countries 
to 
have implemented reforms prior to the collapse of communism -- 
would need several years in order to attain the level of 
economic development required for European Union (EU) 
membership. He added that current reforms had set his country 
"on the right road" and noted that EU membership would be 
important for Hungary's security. 
  Dehaene's trip comes less than two months after the entry 
into force of the Association Treaty between Hungary and the EU. 
  Speaking of the Partnership for Peace -- NATO's initiative 
to 
improve cooperation with its former enemies and which Hungary 
joined on 8 February -- Dehaene confirmed that the 
implementation of this program should perhaps be speeded up. 
  "Hungary signed the Partnership for Peace to be able to move 
closer to NATO, which would represent total security for the 
country," Boross said at the same news conference. 
  Hungary is ready to compromise on the question of national 
minorities, added Boross, referring to the conference on 
stability in Europe convened at the proposal of French Prime 
Minister Edouard Balladur and to be held in Paris on 26 and 27 
May to discuss the situation of minorities. 
  Dehaene is to lunch on Tuesday with the Hungarian secretary 
of state for minorities. He will also meet representatives from 
the opposition parties in parliament, namely the SzDSz [Alliance 
of Free Democrats], the Socialist Party (the former Communist 
MSZP or Hungarian Socialist Party), and the Fidesz [Federation 
of Young Democrats]. After a sightseeing tour of Budapest, he 
will return to Brussels on Tuesday afternoon. 

</TEXT>

