<H3> <TI>   Belgian Prime Minister Makes Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets Party Leaders, Departs </H4>
<F P=102> AU2203204794 Budapest MTI in English 1929 GMT 22 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 22 March (MTI) -- As was reported 
earlier, Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene met with 
leaders of several Hungarian parliamentary parties on Tuesday 
[22 March], prior to leaving Budapest. 
  Chairman of the Hungarian Democratic Forum [MDF] Lajos Fur 
said the parliamentary elections scheduled for May will be vital 
to the future of the Hungarian nation. Following the creation 
of the system of political institutions, the switch to a social 
market economy must be implemented in the next four years, he 
said. 
  Viktor Orban, chairman of the Federation of Young Democrats 
[Fidesz], stressed that the opposition parties are also 
committed to Hungary's membership in the European Union. 
  During his meeting with the Belgian prime minister, Chairman 
of the Alliance of Free Democrats [SZDSZ] Ivan Peto, stressed 
the importance of the May parliamentary elections in terms of 
the young Hungarian democracy. He noted that both society and 
politicians are only now learning of the consequences that can 
accompany a possible change in government within a democratic 
system. 
  Gyula Horn, chairman of the Hungarian Socialist Party 
[MSZP], 
told Dehaene that the MSZP supports NATO's peace-partnership 
conception. Perhaps the only objection would be that, in cases 
of conflict, the consultation opportunities seem weak. 
  Dehaene was seen off at Budapest's Ferihegy Airport by 
Chairman of the Christian Democratic People's Party Laszlo 
Surjan. In the course of their brief discussions, the Belgian 
prime minister stressed high appreciation for the political 
stability experienced, which is unique in the region. 

</TEXT>

