<H3> <TI>   Ukraine's Zlenko Visits, Meets With Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets With Walesa, Pawlak </H4>
<F P=102> LD2203205994 Warsaw PAP in English 2048 GMT 22 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2203205994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, March 22 -- President Lech Walesa on Tuesday 
received visiting Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko to 
discuss ways of broadening Polish-Ukrainian cooperation and to 
fill the existing agreements with "concrete substance." 
  Lech Walesa said that Poland understands problems faced by 
Ukraine. "Ukraine may become a great country but it must gain 
economic independence. And we will strive for such 
independence," the president said. 
  He confirmed his earlier statements that there is no free 
Poland without free Ukraine and said that what we need now are 
actions, we should look for possibilities of close, concrete 
cooperation. 
  Also Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak received the Ukrainian 
guest to discuss the most important issues in relations between 
both neighbours. Both politicians agreed that their countries 
are failing to use up all possibilities of cooperation at 
present. 
  Deputy Senate Speaker Zofia Kuratowska and the Ukrainian 
foreign minister agreed that geographical location of Poland and 
Ukraine was of strategic significance for the security of Europe 
and stressed the need for developing close economic as well as 
political and cultural contacts. 
  Both sides examined also national minority questions in the 
two countries, with Kuratowska deeming it necessary to hold a 
bilateral working conference to review minority questions. 
  Foreign Minister Andrzej Olechowski and the Ukrainian guest 
signed a declaration on principles of shaping Polish-Ukrainian 
partnership and agreement on protection of graves and 
remembrance sites. 
  Zlenko told reporters that the ensuring of national security 
of both countries should become a strategic basis for 
partnership between Poland and Ukraine. 
  In the Centre for Eastern Studies he spoke about current 
international situation and the Ukrainian foreign policy. 

</TEXT>

