<H3> <TI>   Hungarian Official Stresses Need for Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203192894 Budapest MTI in English 1749 GMT 22 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203192894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 22 March (MTI) -- Hungary may submit its 
membership application to the European Union on March 31, and it 
seems probable that Poland will take the same step at that time, 
State Secretary of the Hungarian Foreign Ministry Janos Martonyi 
told MTI's Warsaw correspondent. 
  Martonyi arrived for a visit to Poland on Saturday [19 
March] 
to open the Hungarian Consulate in Krakow, for the time being 
only a symbol, as actual work will begin later. The state 
secretary said the main aim of his visit was to hold 
consultations with senior officials from the Polish Foreign 
Ministry, mainly in an effort to coordinate European integration 
policy. 
  "The reason is that we consider Polish-Hungarian cooperation 
to be of strategic importance, and this remains key to the whole 
of the region," Martonyi said. 
  Talks with Foreign Minister Andrzej Olechowski and his 
assistants, and with members of Polish Parliament's Foreign 
Affairs and European Relations Committees, served this end, as 
well as the furthering of bilateral relations. 
  Martonyi said that like the Hungarian, Polish foreign policy 
also considers the Visegrad cooperation (between Poland, Czech 
Republic, Slovakia, and Hungary) to be alive and important. The 
free trade zone taking shape creates a good basis for developing 
relations in other areas as well. 

</TEXT>

