<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Support Rail Line to Moldova </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203171194 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1502 GMT 22 Mar 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203171194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 22/3/1994 -- A main railway with 
higher speed and European gauges on the Iasi (Romania)-Chisinau 
(Republic of Moldova) route will be built with financial support 
given by Romania's Government, told daily VOCEA ROMANIEI Teodor 
Groza, secretary of state, head of the railway department. The 
funding, worth 95 million lei, including 70 million lei for the 
drawing up of technical studies on the integration of the 
Ungheni (customs point)-Chisinau railway in the European 
transportation network, and 25 million lei for the technical 
surveys on the rebuilding of an important railway section in the 
Republic of Moldova, were earmarked under a Romanian Government 
resolution out of the fund placed at the Romanian Government's 
disposal for the relations with the Republic of Moldova for 
1993. The state secretary said that experts of the railway 
transportation ministries of the two states held several 
meetings to discuss "the integration of the railway 
transportation of the Republic of Moldova in the European 
transportation." 
  Teodor Groza said in the interview that the Romanian party 
offered the railways of the Republic of Moldova the possibility 
of having the equipment repaired in workshops in Romania. As a 
member of the Inter-Ministerial Committee for Romania's 
Relations with the Republic of Moldova, Teodor Groza said that 
the Romanian party gave Moldova assistance in the working out of 
technical surveys on railways, tariff policy, and training of 
personnel. 
  As for road transportation, he said, Romania's Government 
will give financial support for the repair of the bridge across 
the Prut River at Radauti-Lipcani, and is seeking technical 
solutions for the building of a road bridge at Ungheni. 

</TEXT>

