<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gatsinski Views Khan Kubrat Hijacking Affair </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2303135694 Sofia BULGARSKA ARMIYA in Bulgarian 17 Mar 94 
pp 1, 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU2303135694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BULGARSKA ARMIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with First Deputy Foreign Minister Valentin </F>
Gatsinski by Plamen Tsvetkov; place and date not given: "The 
Investigation Will Reveal the Truth"] 
  [Text] [Tsvetkov] Was the hijacking of the Khan Kubrat 
vessel proven in the final analysis? 
  [[Gatsinski] The investigation will clarify the 
circumstances under which the vessel left the Bulgarian section 
of the Danube. 
  [Tsvetkov] Have any hijackers been identified? 
  [Gatsinski] The names of the crew members and the others on 
board are known. The investigation will determine whether some 
of them could be described in the way your question implies. 
  [Tsvetkov] Will the incident affect relations between 
Bulgaria and Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro)? 
  [Gatsinski] Unfortunately, in contrast with their initially 
declared readiness, the Serbian authorities did not cooperate in 
returning not only the crew, but only the vessel's cargo. 
Despite all this, I believe that after the comprehensive crisis 
in Yugoslavia ends the new states that have emerged there will 
find the place they deserve in Europe. I am convinced that in 
the process of normalizing the status of Yugoslavia (Serbia and 
Montenegro) in the international community our relations will 
develop actively as good neighbors, on the basis of mutual 
economic benefit. 
  [Tsvetkov] Would you like to forecast a new development, or 
do you consider the case closed? 
  [Gatsinski] The case will be closed after the investigation 
ends and the culprits are punished. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9369 </DOCNO>
