<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Hijack UN Aid Convoy Heading for Maglaj </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2303190894 Paris AFP in English 1858 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2303190894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 23 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb forces 
Wednesday [23 March] hijacked a 10-truck UN aid convoy headed 
for the northern town of Maglaj and briefly abducted the 
drivers, the United Nations said. 
  The trucks had left Zagreb in the morning with 90 tonnes of 
food and other relief material and were seized in the Tezlic 
region southwest of the Moslem city, officials said. The 
drivers were abducted and held for several hours, and turned up 
later in the town of Zepce, controlled by Bosnian Croat forces, 
said Kris Janowski, a spokesman for the United Nations High 
Commissioner for Refugees. 
  "It's a very serious incident," he said. One of the trucks 
was later recovered but it was empty, he added. 
  Maglaj received its first aid convoy in five months on 
Sunday 
after Serb forces that had been attacking it eased their siege. 
The town has a population of around 16,000. 

</TEXT>

