<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Admits Serbs Responsible </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403141594 Paris AFP in English 1345 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2403141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 24 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic has promised his forces will return nine UN 
aid-convoy trucks stolen near the northern town of Maglaj, the 
UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said Thursday [24 
March]. A meeting was scheduled later Thursday in the Bosnian 
Serb stronghold of Pale between the head of the UNHCR mission in 
Bosnia-Hercegovina, Karin Abu-Zayd, and the separatist 
republic's vice-president Nikola Koljevic, said UNHCR spokesman 
Kris Janowski. 
  Karadzic had personally assured UN special representative to 
ex-Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi the trucks would be returned as 
soon as possible, Janowski said. Convoys would again start 
moving from the Croatian capital Zagreb to the Maglaj region 
once the United Nations obtained security guarantees, he said, 
adding that convoys however were still leaving from Zenica, in 
central Bosnia. 
  The stolen trucks were parked at a Bosnian Serb barracks in 
Tezlic, southwest of Maglaj, a mainly-Moslem enclave which 
received its first aid convoy in five months on Sunday after 
Serb forces eased their siege, the spokesman said. 
  Rogue Bosnian Serb forces hijacked a 10-truck UN aid convoy 
taking 94 tonnes of food and other aid to Maglaj on Wednesday 
near Teslic. Serb soldiers, led by a colonel whom Karadzic said 
would be punished, threatened the Danish drivers and forced them 
to abandon the trucks, Jankowski said. The Serbs starting 
loading the trucks' contents onto civilian trucks, but when it 
turned out to be a lengthy operation, they stole the trucks, the 
spokesman said, adding that Serb police guarding the convoy 
"evaporated." The Danish drivers were abducted, then found a few 
hours later at Zepce, about 30 kilometers (20 miles) to the 
south, in a Bosnian Croat-held area. One of the trucks was 
recovered later, he said. 
  Jankowski described the theft as a "very serious incident." 
He said Pale late Wednesday "declared itself quite upset and 
surprised" at what had happened. 
  Two UNHCR convoys have reached Maglaj from Zenica and two 
others from Tesanj, north of Maglaj, since British UN 
peacekeepers entered the town Sunday. Before that, the town of 
16,000 had been supplied for the past five months mainly by air 
drops. No convoys had been sent in since October, when two 
Danish drivers of a UNHCR convoy were assassinated as they were 
entering Maglaj. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9380 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu057_i_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-057 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

