<H3> <TI>   EU Names Civil Administrator </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403113194 Paris AFP in English 1121 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2403113194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, March 24 (AFP) -- Germany is to provide a 
civil administrator for the war-torn Bosnia-Herzegovina town of 
Mostar on behalf of the European Union, a source close to the 
nominee confirmed Thursday [24 March]. 
  The Social Democrat (SPD) former mayor of Bremen, Hans 
Kochnick, has been named by the European Union in agreement with 
the German government, SPD foreign affairs official Karsten 
Voigt told AFP. 
  Voigt said it had been envisaged for some time to send 
Kochnick to the town as its administrator, and this was set to 
materialise "as peace slowly comes to Bosnia-Herzegovina". 
  DER SPIEGEL magazine reported a month ago that a German 
civil 
administrator was to be sent to Mostar, and would be assisted in 
restoring public services by German police and civil servants. 
  Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Wednesday that he favoured 
Germany taking a role in reconstruction efforts in former 
Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

