<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Decision To Send Turkish Troops Condemned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2403125094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1212 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2403125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Dusan Zupan] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 24 (TANJUG) -- A report from the 
United Nations that the Security Council agrees to Turkey's 
sending its troops to the former Yugoslav Republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina unavoidably arouse associations on the 
stories about a goat which is supposed to watch over the cabbage 
and a wolf which is supposed to protect the sheep. 
  Such lack of sensitivity on the part of the U.N., which is 
sending to Bosnia-Herzegovina troops whose government has long 
since declared itself clearly on whose side it is, is simply 
amazing. Turkey has assisted Bosnian Moslems from the first day 
of their secession -- politically, militarily, financially, 
morally. Turkish war correspondents, have publicly boasted in 
their papers of having shot at and killed "infidels". If this 
is so among reporters then what may one expect the Turkish 
troops might do. 
  By adopting the stand that Turkey may send troops to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, the U.N. has broken its own vow that former 
occupying forces could not be among the U.N. peacekeeping force 
in a respective country. Turks have been occupiers on the 
territory of Bosnia-Herzegovina for full 500 years. 
  For the Bosnian Moslems, Turkey means incomparably more than 
Russia does to the Serbs. Even the family of Bosnian Moslem 
leader Alija Izetbegovic lives in Turkey. On the other side, 
Russia has never been an occupying force on these territories, 
nor has its troops impaled the Moslems here. However, as 
regards the Serbs and Turks -- it is different story. 
  All in all, the U.N. decision, among many others which it 
took under pressure, testifies about further moral degradation 
of the world organization. Moral strength has always been its 
mightiest weapon, now this too is lost. 
  If the Turks, nevertheless, arrive to Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
the 
only true balance might be achieved by calling on the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia to send its troops there too. Everything 
else looks as poorly veiled hypocrisy the objective of which is 
to threaten the lives of Serbs and their property, and this not 
only in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

