<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supports Czech EU Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103193894 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1700 
GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2103193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Prague today, Belgian Vice Prime Minister and 
Foreign Minister Willy Claes, Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus, 
and Foreign Minister Jozef Zieleniec discussed relations between 
the Czech Republic and the Kingdom of Belgium. Mutual 
multilateral relations in connection with the Czech Republic's 
effort aimed at joining the European Union were also discussed. 
Klara Stejskalova reports: 
  [Stejskalova] All of the representatives jointly praised the 
good and intensive relations between the two countries, evidence 
of which is the unusual interest of Belgian entrepreneurs in our 
country, Josef Zieleniec said. Over the past year alone, the 
Belgians have invested more than $150 million in our country. 
Thus, they rank fourth among foreign investors. 
  Regarding Czech membership in the European Union, Claes 
expressed complete support for the Czech Republic. At the same 
time, he praised the democratization of politics in our country 
and the path toward a very strong economy that we have embarked 
upon. In conclusion, he said that those West Europeans who 
think they live on an isolated island are naive. He said that 
support for the process of integration is in the interest of the 
European Union. Integration should take place gradually and not 
in blocks. It should be based solely on the fulfillment of the 
necessary conditions by individual countries. It cannot be 
expected, however, that European Union enlargement could take 
place before the intergovernmental conference of the European 
Union states, scheduled to take place in 1996. 

</TEXT>

