<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soros Stake in RFE Would Jeopardize Move </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403082894 Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES in Czech 22 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2403082894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "jik": "Radio Free Europe Can Come to Prague, </F>
but Only Without Soros"] 
  [Text] Should the U.S. Administration, which finances Radio 
Free Europe [RFE], agree to U.S. businessman George Soros's 
investing millions of dollars in the station, negotiations with 
the Czech Government about the RFE's relocation to the building 
of the former Federal Assembly in Prague would be seriously 
jeopardized. This was declared by Minister [of Control] Igor 
Nemec yesterday. 
  THE NEW YORK TIMES wrote on Sunday [20 March] that the RFE 
was expected to reach an agreement with Soros within one month 
about the privatization of its research center and archives and 
their relocation from Munich to Prague. 
  The government is determined to finance the operation of the 
currently unoccupied building of the Federal Assembly until the 
end of this month. Should RFE move into the building, it ought 
to finance the operation of the building as of April. The 
building is to be leased to it for only a symbolic sum. Should 
Soros become involved in the radio as an investor, however, the 
Czech Government would have no reason, according to Nemec, not 
to lease the Federal Assembly building to someone else at a 
market price. "There are hundreds of interested parties," Nemec 
said. 

</TEXT>

