<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhelev Against Balkan Troops in UNPROFOR </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403104494 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1000 
GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2403104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Zhelyu Zhelev has written to UN General 
Secretary Butrus Butrus-Ghali pointing out that the Balkan 
countries are burdened by their past, and that any military 
intervention by a Balkan country in Bosnia-Herzegovina, even as 
part of the Blue Helmet forces and even when prompted by the 
noblest of motives, could evoke old suspicions and animosity. 
  While the president expresses understanding for the growing 
need to increase the number of Blue Helmets, without which the 
agreements that have been reached could not be implemented, he 
points out that there is an even greater risk if soldiers from 
any Balkan country participate in the Blue Helmets. 
  President Zhelev expresses confidence that the UN general 
secretary is aware of this danger and will continue his efforts 
to seek an appropriate solution on the part of the world 
organization. 
  The Bulgarian president recalls that since the beginning of 
the crisis Bulgaria has repeatedly declared that it will not 
take advantage of the situation and will not participate in any 
military way in the events in former Yugoslavia. Bulgaria also 
appealed to the other neighboring Balkan states to do the same. 
  The president also recalls the strict observance of the UN 
embargo against Serbia and Montenegro, and stresses that, 
despite its great losses and difficulties, Bulgaria will 
continue to follow this policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

