<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks on Dividing Yugoslav Assets `Deadlocked' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1803142594 Paris AFP in English 1410 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1803142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, March 18 (AFP) -- The latest round of talks 
on the division of former Yugoslavia's assets were deadlocked 
Friday [18 March] due to Belgrade's failure to provide realistic 
figures, diplomatic sources said. 
  Talks reopened Thursday and were continuing Friday between 
the rump state of Yugoslavia, made up of Serbia and Montenegro, 
and the other former Yugoslav republics of Slovenia, Croatia, 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic 
of Macedonia -- FYROM], Geneva peace conference spokesman John 
Mills said. 
  But non-Serb sources said the talks were as unproductive as 
earlier sessions because the Serbian authorities refused to 
provide documents needed for a realistic evaluation of the 
former state's assets. 
  Mills said talks by the working group, headed by Danish 
ambassador to Berne Els Johansson, would be "a drawn-out 
process." 
  Another ex-Yugoslav working group, on humanitarian issues, 
was due to meet Friday afternoon in Geneva headed by Sadako 
Ogata of the UN High Commission for Refugees who returned 
recently from a visit to Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

