<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgian Prime Minister Makes Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hears Opposition Views on EU </H4>
<F P=102> LD2203132494 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1100 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2203132494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene, who is in 
Budapest on an official visit, was briefed this morning about 
the situation of the minorities in Hungary. He then met leaders 
of the three largest opposition parties. Anna Gulyas reports: 
  [Gulyas] We told the prime minister that when judging the 
situation in Hungary it is necessary to consider the fact that, 
bearing in mind that these are the second free, democratic 
elections, neither the politicians nor public opinion have 
really learned the rules of the game, Ivan Petoe, chairman of 
the Alliance of Free Democrats [SZDSZ], said in a statement 
summing up the discussion. He added: The room for maneuver in 
forming coalitions is influenced by the fact that not only 
rational but very often emotional factors have an impact on the 
parties' coalition plans in Hungary. 
  Gyula Horn, chairman of the Hungarian Socialist Party [HSP], 
called the attention of Jean-Luc Dehaene to the fact that the 
European Union should take greater account of the 
characteristics of the region's countries. It would be good if 
Brussels acknowledges the achievements of the states concerned 
-- including those of our country -- in the development of a 
market economy, and if it desists from treating the issue of the 
east-central European countries' accession as one package. 
  In connection with NATO, we accept that the region must be 
treated as a unified whole, Gyula Horn said, adding that during 
the discussion he emphasized the Socialist Party's opinion that 
in Hungary a referendum should precede NATO accession. 
  The Hungarian political parties are committed to membership 
in NATO and the European Union. This was also affirmed by 
Viktor Orban, chairman of the Federation of Young Democrats 
[Fidesz], at the discussion. 
  In connection with full membership in the European Union, 
the 
Belgian prime minister again highlighted the importance of 
preparation. The extent of this influences the time it takes to 
gain membership. 

</TEXT>

