<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgian Prime Minister Makes Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   NATO, EU Membership Discussed </H4>
<F P=102> BR2403152494 Antwerp DE FINANCIEEL-EKONOMISCHE TIJD in Dutch 
24 Mar 94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> BR2403152494 </F>
<F P=104>  Antwerp DE FINANCIEEL-EKONOMISCHE TIJD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed LDV: "Hungary Not Put Off by European Union </F>
Crisis. Membership Request on 1 April"] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] 
<H5>  NATO </H5>
  After meeting with his Hungarian counterpart, Prime Minister 
Dehaene emphasized that Hungary's integration is a gradual 
process. This does not only apply to EU membership but also to 
NATO membership. The Partnership for Peace is a first step in 
that direction. 
  During his official contacts, however, the Belgian prime 
minister found out that the Hungarian socialists are not so keen 
on joining NATO. The socialists argue that they are not at all 
sure that the population wants such a membership. 
  In Hungary there has been quite a noise about NATO Air Force 
General Kehoe's statement that NATO's AWACS airplanes operating 
in Hungarian airspace were directly involved in the shooting 
down of four Serbian military airplanes by U.S. airplanes at the 
end of last month. 
  On 11 February Prime Minister Boross had ruled that the 
AWACS 
airplanes would not be allowed to use the Hungarian airspace if 
NATO was going to launch air strikes against Bosnian Serb 
positions around Sarajevo. The prime minister justified this 
unexpected decision by referring, among other things, to the 
difficult situation of the 430,000 or so ethnic Hungarians 
living in the Province of Vojvodina, which is part of Serbia. 
  The problem of the minorities was also one of the issues 
Prime Minister Dehaene brought up in Budapest during his meeting 
with the relevant state secretaries. On 7 July 1993 the 
Hungarian parliament passed a law on national and ethnic 
minorities. According to Dehaene, the law on minorities contains 
clauses which are not applicable to Hungary and is mainly 
intended as a signal to the neighboring countries, including 
Serbia and Montenegro. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9466 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu058_b_94001" </HT>


