<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Granic Discusses Negotiations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403164594 Paris AFP in English 1620 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2403164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Helsinki, March 24 (AFP) -- Croatian Foreign 
Minister Mate Granic expressed hope Thursday that negotiations 
with separatist Serbs in the disputed Krajina region in southern 
Croatia would lead to an overall ceasefire. 
  "I'm hopeful," Granic said at a brief press conference after 
talks with Finnish leaders. Granic also said Zagreb was ready to 
grant limited autonomy to Krajina Serbs but ruled out full 
"independence" as demanded by local Serbs. 
  The first round of negotiations between Croatian officials 
and Croatian Serb leaders in Zagreb were adjourned early 
Wednesday but the two sides agreed to meet again next week. The 
negotiations at the Russian Embassy were the first of its kind 
to be held in Zagreb under the auspices of the United Nations 
Protection Force (UNPROFOR). Granic, who arrived here Wednesday 
evening on a 24-hour visit, had talks Thursday with Finnish 
President Martti Ahtisaari, Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto, 
parliamentary speaker Riitta Uosukainen and the chairman of the 
parliamentary foreign affairs committee Pertti Paasio. 
  Granic said he had briefed Finnish leaders on the situation 
in his country and Croatian policy on the former Yugoslavia. 
Ahtisaari, who earlier this year was elected Finland's head of 
state, was himself involved last year in Yugoslavia peace talks 
in Geneva as a special representative of UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali. Helsinki was the last leg of Granic's 
Nordic tour that also included stops in Oslo, Stockholm and 
Copenhagen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9472 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu058_i_94002" </HT>


