<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges Assembly Not To Join Federation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403200094 Paris AFP in English 1945 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2403200094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 24 (AFP) -- Radovan Karadzic urged 
the Bosnian Serbs' self-styled parliament not to sign on to a 
new Croat-Moslem federation agreement but refused to rule out 
other kinds of ties with the entity. 
  Speaking in the Bosnian Serb stronghold of Pale near 
Sarajevo, the Bosnian Serb leader urged the lawmakers "to reject 
out of hand all participation in the new Croat-Moslem 
federation." 
  But he said he "did not rule out the possibility of 
establishing various types of ties with the newly created state, 
but not federal ties." 
  An agreement to create the federation was signed last Friday 
in Washington by Bosnian Croat and Moslem leaders. It is 
designed to put pressure on the Serbs, who control most of 
Bosnia after nearly two years of war, to end the fighting. 
  Karadzic said the Bosnian Serbs wanted "a sovereign and 
independent state" and would consider at some point in the 
future their relations with the former Yugoslav republics. 
  He said he was willing to recognize the new federation "so 
long as the Serbs obtain access to the sea." This was seen as 
signaling willingness to give up conquered land. 
  The United States and Russia have been trying to get the 
Bosnian Serbs to join up with the new federation as a way of 
maintaining Bosnia as something resembling a unified state. The 
federation is currently designed to cover half of Bosnia's land, 
but the Serbs control around 70 percent of the republic's 
territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9474 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu058_i_94004" </HT>


