<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Warning on Troops Highlighted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2403194094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1750 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2403194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 24 (TANJUG) -- The president of the 
Bosnian Serb Republic (RS), Radovan Karadzic warned on Thursday 
that the decision to deploy Turkish U.N. troops in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina would create conditions for a major Balkan 
war. 
  Karadzic told a RS parliamentary session in Pale, RS 
political centre close to Sarajevo, that if Turkish soldiers are 
sent to the Moslem-Croat state in Bosnia, the Bosnian Serbs 
would demand that in its territory are deployed the troops of 
the neighbouring Federal Republic of Yugoslavia as a U.N. 
member, said Bosnian Serb news agency SRNA. 
  The United Nations has so far operated on the principle not 
to deploy troops of neighbouring countries and earlier occupiers 
in the territory of the former Yugoslavia. 
  The region of Bosnia-Herzegovina was for 500 years (until 
the 
beginning of the 20th century) under Turkish occupation, and 
this is still vivid in the memories of the Bosnian population, 
especially the Serbs. 
  However, the U.N. Security Council on Wednesday gave the 
go-ahead to a proposal by the secretary-general that Turkish 
peacekeepers be deployed in Bosnia and passed on the final 
decision to Butrus-Ghali. 
  The latest reports from the U.N. New York headquarters are 
that the Turkish U.N. contigent should be deployed along the 
separation lines between the Bosnian Moslems and Croats, who 
succumbed to strong U.S. pressure last week and signed an accord 
on setting up their federation in Bosnia. 
  Karadzic informed the parliamentary session about the 
outcome 
of the peace talks on Bosnia held so far and the proposal to 
determine a new platform for their continuation. 
  Karadzic suggested to the deputies to adopt a platform which 
would include a demand for establishing peace, just territorial 
delimitation, the rejection of the Serb participation in the 
Moslem-Croat federation and which would insist on the Serbs' 
right to self-determination. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

