<H3> <TI>   Sarajevo Radio Rounds Up Combat Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403161794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2403161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] After fierce chetnik attacks and after yet another 
attempt by the aggressor forces to make further advances, a 
general danger alarm was sounded in Zavidovici. The chetnik 
advance was nevertheless halted by a successful counteroffensive 
by our fighters. 
  The usual chetnik provocations also continued on the free 
territory of Zvornik. However, demonstrating their courage, our 
defenders have again been very successful. Today, the enemy 
also pounded the city center of Olovo and the positions of our 
defenders. Like all other attempts by the aggressor to breach 
the lines of our defense, this one was also unsuccessful. 
  This morning, the chetniks opened sniper fire on Kasindol 
street from the Bosut Barracks. The aggressor attacked Dobrinja 
with infantry weapons from Nedjarici. Stup was attacked with 
bombs fired from portable mortars. This was reported by the 
Information Service of the 1st Army Corps. 
  The ferocity of the chetnik attacks in the zone of 
operations 
of the 3d Army Corps was offset by the defenders-members of the 
Army of the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, inflicting great 
losses on them in manpower and equipment. They are also 
liberating parts of occupied territories. Since it cannot do 
anything else, the aggressor is shelling villages, towns, and 
the civilian population. There have been no violations of the 
cease-fire agreement reached by the Army of Bosnia-Herzegovina 
and the Croatian Defense Council [HVO] in this region. The 
truce is generally holding at other lines of separation. 
  In line with the agreement reached the day before yesterday 
by the negotiating teams of the Army of the Republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, the aggressor side, and the representatives 
of UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces], three prisoners held by the 
aggressor soldiers in Silos prison in (?Tarcin) were exchanged 
for three civilians from Kula prison. 
  The process of exchanging prisoners is the first and the 
most 
controversial point in the Silajdzic-Krajisnik negotiations. 
The realization of other points from this agreement did not 
take place because of the lack of cooperation by the aggressor 
side. So, the issue of Silos and the 189 missing Bosniaks, who, 
according to their families, were taken by the terrorist chetnik 
forces to an unknown destination, remains unresolved. 

</TEXT>

