<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb Treatment of UNHCR Drivers Detailed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403170894 Paris AFP in English 1653 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2403170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, March 24 (AFP) -- Ten Danish drivers were 
lined up against a wall and "feared that they would be shot" 
after their relief trucks were stolen by Bosnian Serb soldiers 
near the northern Bosnian town of Maglaj, a UN spokesman said 
here Thursday. Later they were forced to walk for about a 
kilometre through no-man's-land between Bosnian Serb and Croat 
forces, before being taken to a UN Protection Force post by 
Croats. After the theft of their vehicles, the drivers were 
loaded into a lorry and taken towards the nearby front line, UN 
High Commissioner for Refugees [UNHCR] spokesman Peter Kessler 
said. "They were then lined up in front of a house. At this 
point it became very, very terrifying for them," he said. "They 
were told to empty their pockets, to give their belongings to 
the Bosnian Serbs. When they saw their personal property being 
thrown on the ground they then feared that they would be shot." 
After being searched the UNHCR drivers were told to walk on 
their own to a minefield, holding white flags over their heads 
and to look out for snipers as it was no-man's-land. It was only 
after walking about a kilometre they located a post manned by 
Bosnian Croat HVO [Croatian Defense Council] forces at Zepce, 
about 30 kilometres (20 miles) south of where they were 
abducted. The Croats drove the team to a UN Protection Force 
[UNPROFOR] base. "The entire situation was terrifying for the 
convoy team," Kessler said. 
  Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic earlier Thursday told 
Yasushi Akashi, the UN secretary-general's special envoy in 
former Yugoslavia, that the local Serb commander had acted 
without authorisation. He would be punished, Karadzic said, 
according to Kessler. The Serb leader also promised his forces 
would return the nine stolen UN aid-convoy trucks which have 
since been located. 
  Convoys would again start moving from the Croatian capital 
Zagreb to the Maglaj region once the United Nations obtained 
security guarantees, said UNHCR spokesman Kris Janowski, adding 
that convoys were nevertheless still leaving from Zenica, in 
central Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

