<H3> <TI>   Kontic Chairs Government Session, Reviews Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2403211894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1358 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2403211894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Belgrade, 24 Mar (TANJUG) -- At today's Federal 
Government session, chaired by Prime Minister Radoje Kontic, the 
government reviewed a report on current issues concerning the 
position of members of the nations of the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia [FRY] in other countries, as well as the position of 
members of the Serb and Montenegrin nations living in the 
territory of the former Socialist Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia, which are now outside the territory of Yugoslavia. 
  The Ministry of Information has announced that on the basis 
of this report and the ensuing discussion, the Federal 
Government will adopt special conclusions at one of its future 
sessions. [passage omitted] 
  In a report dealing with requests by certain international 
bodies and organizations to send permanent missions or 
representatives to Kosovo-Metohija, the government noted a clear 
tendency to put forward such requests to replace the suspended 
CSCE mission. 
  The government concluded that for reasons of principle the 
FRY cannot accept requests for a CERD [as received] mission and 
UNESCO representatives to be sent to Yugoslavia and to have a 
seat in Kosovo-Metohija because Yugoslavia as a state is not 
allowed to participate in the work of these bodies and 
organizations as an equal participant. 
  As proof of good will, the Federal Government concluded that 
Yugoslavia still expresses full readiness for dialogue and more 
intensive cooperation on an equal basis with those bodies and 
organizations -- of which Yugoslavia is a signatory, initiator 
and founder -- which is in mutual interest and in the interest 
of peace, security and cooperation in Europe and the world. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

