<H3> <TI>   Russia To Continue Humanitarian Aid </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2303171894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1350 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2303171894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 23 Mar (TANJUG) -- Jovan Zebic, vice 
president of the Federal Government, had talks in the Palace of 
Federation today with Gennadiy Shikin, ambassador of the Russian 
Federation in Belgrade. 
  As the Ministry for Information reports, they talked about 
providing humanitarian aid to Yugoslavia and preparations for 
resuming economic cooperation between the two countries 
following the lifting of sanctions. 
  Vice President Zebic thanked Ambassador Shikin for Russia's 
humanitarian efforts and its initiatives for reaching a lasting 
agreement on a peaceful solution to the crisis in the former 
Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina that would be acceptable 
to all three warring sides. 
  Ambassador Shikin stated that, unfortunately, Russia's 
efforts in providing humanitarian aid to Yugoslavia have so far 
failed to yield any major result due to the unconstructive and 
unreasonable conduct of some countries in the UN Security 
Council's sanctions committee. Ambassador Shikin noted, 
however, that Russia will continue its efforts to endorse 
humanitarian aid for Yugoslavia, the Ministry for Information 
says in its statement. 

</TEXT>

