<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zeman Accused of Trying To Restore CSFR </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2303154894 Prague CTK in English 1040 GMT 23 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2303154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 23 (CTK) -- According to some 
Bratislava officials, Czech Social Democratic Party (CSSD) 
Chairman Milos Zeman has informed leaders of the Slovak Social 
Democrats and Democratic Left Party (SDL) of his intention to 
make a new endeavor to create the Czechoslovak union, Robert 
Casensky and Michal Musil from Bratislava say in the 
right-oriented daily TELEGRAF today. 
  According to Zeman's plan, a referendum should decide on the 
issue. Although the information has been confirmed by Frantisek 
Miklosko, chairman of the Christian Democratic Movement (KDH) 
Deputies' Group, and indirectly by SDL Chairman Peter Weiss, 
Zeman asserts that he did not make such a statement. 
  "Should such an offer be made I will comment on it," Zeman 
said. However, if some Slovak political parties consider such a 
proposal then it is "their own business" and the CSSD would not 
interfere in it, Zeman said. 
  Miklosko asserts, however, that Zeman has actually come up 
with such an initiative at talks with representatives of the 
Slovak Social Democratic Party (SSDS) and part of the SDL. 
Miklosko said that according to information he possessed, the 
CSSD is planning to include the creation of the union in its 
election program. Slovak political parties had not, however, 
shown much interest in Zeman's initiative. "I personally believe 
that the Slovak left will not be strong enough to carry out the 
idea. Mr. Zeman has much bigger aspirations in this respect," 
Miklosko said. 
  Weiss did not refute Miklosko's information. Asked directly 
what his party's stand has on the proposal by the Czech Social 
Democrats, Weiss said that the SDL saw the division of 
Czechoslovakia as a fait accompli. "The independence of both the 
Czech and Slovak Republics is a reality and there is no point in 
changing it," Weiss said, adding that there were neither 
internal political nor external political conditions for the 
renewal of something which was once here. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9535 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu058__a94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-058-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   CSSD Official on `Misunderstanding' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403131094 Prague CTK in English 1621 GMT 23 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2403131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 23 (CTK) -- Pavel Novak, deputy 
chairman of the Czech Social Democratic Party (CSSD), told CTK 
he considered the information published in the right-oriented 
daily TELEGRAF today that CSSD Chairman Milos Zeman intended to 
renew the "Czechoslovak union", to be a misunderstanding. 
  TELEGRAF writes that Frantisek Miklosko, chairman of the 
deputies group of Slovakia's Christian Democratic Movement 
(KDH), said that "Zeman submitted such an initiative during his 
talks with the Slovak Social Democrats and part of (Slovakia's) 
Democratic Left Party (SDL)...and according to his (Miklosko's) 
information, the CSSD planned to include such an initiative into 
its election program." 
  Novak said he spoke to Zeman every day but they had never 
discussed such an initiative. He stressed that representatives 
of social democracy had never discussed "a similar project" 
either with Miklosko or SDL leaders, or leaders of the Social 
Democratic Party in Slovakia (SDSS). CSSD has not dealt with 
these questions since the split of the Czechoslovak Federation 
on January 1, 1993, Novak said. 
  He stressed that the activity of Zeman as deputy to the now 
defunct federal parliament in late 1992, by which he pushed for 
the unity of the country, had not represented CSSD policy. 
Zeman then had "only certain support" within the party, but not 
of its central boards. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

