<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Rejects Idea of Czech-Slovak Union </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403164794 Prague CTK in English 1513 GMT 24 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2403164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 24 (CTK) -- Premier Jozef 
Moravcik told Slovak Radio today he rejected the idea of the 
Czech-Slovak union and called it a wasted opportunity a year 
ago. He added that he still believed that since the new state 
emerged it had been out of place to develop the idea of a joint 
entity, he added. 
  The idea was presented by Chairman of the Czech Social 
Democratic Party Milos Zeman at a seminar organized by the 
Slovak Social Democratic Party last year, Moravcik reported. He 
dismissed the rumors that he met Zeman during his Monday's [21 
March] visit to Prague. 
  "I think that the European Union is our future," said 
Moravcik, adding that closer co-existence of the two countries 
will be possible within a wider framework. 
  "None of the Slovak and Czech political parties represented 
in the government are really contemplating the union," stressed 
Moravcik. "These are reminiscences, revived from time to time, 
but without any real substance," he added. 
  Zeman allegedly reiterated the issue during his recent 
meeting with a "part" of the Slovak Democratic Left Party (SDL). 
SDL chairman Peter Weiss did not deny the offer was tendered, 
but stated that the SDL was respecting the situation emerged 
after the split of the common state. 

</TEXT>

