<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik on Government Program Preparations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2603190494 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2603190494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Announcer] Today is not a rest day for the new 
Slovak Government. Members of the Cabinet have been meeting in 
expert groups to prepare their programmatic statement. Our 
correspondent Michal Tvarozek asked Prime Minister Jozef 
Moravcik which were the most important areas, especially in the 
economy, that the government wants to accelerate. 
  [Begin recording] [Moravcik] The most fundamental problem is 
putting together the economic program. The largest group of 
experts is working precisely on this program. We will probably 
have to revise some measures proposed by the previous government 
in preparing the budget. We will have to revise these measures 
to make them more realistic. We will have to do everything 
possible to reach agreement with the international institutions, 
particularly the IMF and the World Bank. 
  In other areas, the most complicated situation has arisen in 
health and education. [passage omitted] 
  [Tvarozek] Presumably the first version of the government's 
program will serve also as a consultative document for, let us 
say, employers, trade unions, all those who have a say as far as 
the government's statement is concerned. 
  [Moravcik] Certainly we have to do this. We have to respect 
the general agreement. The general agreement is for us a very 
important document, and we would like to have observations of 
all involved parties when working on the first version of the 
statement. 
  [Tvarozek] In one hour, you are going to attend the 
extraordinary session of the government. It is possible that 
the agenda will center precisely on the conclusions reached by 
these expert groups. 
  [Moravcik] This session should not deal with specific 
problems. We will discuss where we stand, what we ought to do 
next in terms of next week's work, and we will clarify which are 
the main problems that have arisen when working on these 
materials. 
  [Tvarozek] Let us assume that the National Council will not 
agree with your policy statement. What will happen if it is not 
approved? 
  [Moravcik] I hope it will be approved. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9572 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu059_d_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-059 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

